                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" subtype="imperial"><name><supplied reason="lost">Θεοδ</supplied>οσίο<supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">υ</supplied></name></persName> <w><supplied reason="lost">τὸ</supplied></w> <supplied reason="lost"><num value="15">ιε</num></supplied> <w><supplied reason="lost">καὶ</supplied></w> <persName type="attested" subtype="imperial"><name><supplied reason="lost">Βαλεν</supplied><lb n="3" break="no"/><supplied reason="lost">τινιανοῦ</supplied></name></persName> <w><supplied reason="lost">τ</supplied>ὸ</w> <num value="4">δ</num> <name><expan><abbr>Αὐγ<am>γ</am></abbr><ex>ούστων</ex></expan></name> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character" cert="low"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus" resp="#martaf">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text based on photograph and on Ferrua's edition</note></app>
                    <app loc="line 1"><note>The only trace at l. 1 seems to belong neither to a N nor to a Ω. ΝΩΝ was seen by Amico in 1741.</note></app>
                    <app loc="line 1"><note>According to Korhonen, also μετὰ τὴν ὑπατείαν is possible.</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#martaf #AA">
                <p>... the Nones of ... in the fifteenth consulate of Theodosius and the fourth of Valentinian, the Augusti.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#martaf">
                <p>... le None di ... durante il quindicesimo consolato di Teodosio e il quarto di Valentiniano, gli Augusti.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The inscription is probably the fragment of the end of an epitaph with a consular date: the date on which the deceased died is recorded (the indication <foreign xml:lang="grc">Νων[ῶν]</foreign> must have been accompanied by the day and followed by the month) and the consuls of that year. Ferrua’s supplements are based on the traces at l. 2 <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΟΣΙΟ</foreign>, which could only belong to the name Theodosius and the numeral <foreign xml:lang="grc">δ</foreign> probably indicating the number of the consulate of Theodosius’colleague, both Augusti. The only possibility is then 435 AD, the year of the fifteenth consulate of Theodosius II and the fourth of Valentian III (a date also confirmed by palaeography).</p>
            </div>
